<p>The <a href="http://www.goes.noaa.gov/">GOES (Geostationary Satellite)</a> 
provide the commonly seen views of clouds from space.  The National Weather
Service is now publishing data from these satellites in <a href="http://www.gis.ssd.nesdis.noaa.gov/">GIS formats</a>.  
Thanks to the generous support of <a href="http://www.unidata.ucar.edu">UNIDATA</a>, the IEM processes this data feed and
provides <a href="../ogc/">OGC compliant web services</a> as well as an archive.

<h3>IEM Processing</h3>

<p>Data from the GOES birds is available twice an hour (:15 and :45 after the hour). The most recent product is over 30 minutes old.  The raw data files are
very large (70 MB TIFF images for visible).  The IEM does make these files available, but
they are too large for archiving in their highest resolution form.  For that
reason, the IEM generates a 4km CONUS composite of the East and West GOES birds
for the archive and realtime apps.

<p><b>Please Note:</b>  This still remains a work in progress.  Please let us
know if you have any ideas on how this service can be improved.

